        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Compliance Forms — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "compliance-reference",
            Summary = "Edge-case reference for Compliance Forms: AcroForm field-map + blank PDF setup, auto-sync from source URL, form-definition version pinning, I-9 reverification, sensitive-form masking, DocuSeal recovery, and system vs custom templates.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/compliance"]""",
            Tags = """["compliance","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Compliance Forms — Advanced Reference\n\nEdge-case and ancillary detail for the Compliance Forms area (Admin > Compliance, route /admin/compliance), behind capability **CAP-QC-COMPLIANCE-FORMS**. The core modules cover the everyday flow; this is the side documentation for the mechanics that only matter when you're configuring PDF fill, debugging a stuck form, or handling the I-9 long tail.\n\n## AcroForm Field-Map JSON + Blank PDF Setup\n\nA \"fill-and-sign\" template pre-fills the real government PDF before sending it to DocuSeal. Two template fields drive this:\n\n- **`FilledPdfTemplateId`** — the MinIO file ID of the blank fillable government PDF (the document to fill). Set via the upload dialog's PDF-fill section; a green chip confirms it's linked.\n- **`AcroFieldMapJson`** — a JSON object mapping the dynamic form field IDs (from the extracted ComplianceFormDefinition) to the named AcroForm fields inside that blank PDF. Example shape: `{\"w4FilingStatus\":\"topmostSubform[0].Page1[0].c1_1[0]\",\"firstName\":\"f1_01[0]\"}`.\n\nAt submit time the backend fills the `FilledPdfTemplate` PDF using this map, stores the filled-but-unsigned PDF on the submission (`FilledPdfFileId`), then hands it to DocuSeal. If the map is missing or wrong, the wrong AcroForm field gets the value (or none does) — the signed PDF then doesn't match the collected data. Both fields are required for true PDF fill; a template with an electronic definition but no map/blank PDF still collects data and signs, but doesn't reproduce the official paper layout.\n\n## Auto-Sync from Source URL\n\n`SourceUrl` is the URL of the official government PDF. With **`IsAutoSync` = true**, the system re-pulls that URL on a schedule and on demand. Change detection uses **`Sha256Hash`** — the stored hash of the last-pulled PDF; a sync only re-extracts when the new download's hash differs, so unchanged sources are cheap no-ops. `LastSyncedAt` records the last successful pull (shows as *Never* until the first sync).\n\n- **Sync All** (`POST /sync-all`, header button) re-pulls every auto-sync template.\n- **Row Sync** (`POST /{id}/sync`, `sync` icon) refreshes one template; it appears only on auto-sync templates that have a `SourceUrl`.\n\nA successful sync that detects a new version produces a new `FormDefinitionVersion` (see below) rather than mutating prior versions. Manual templates (auto-sync off) never pull on their own — their definition only changes when an admin re-extracts.\n\n## Form-Definition Version Pinning\n\nEach extraction produces a **`FormDefinitionVersion`** row (template ID, optional state code, `SourceUrl`, effective date, and the full definition JSON). A submission stores **`FormDefinitionVersionId`**, pinning it to the exact layout it was filled against. This is what lets a form be regenerated with its original layout years later, even after the IRS/USCIS revises the form and a newer version is extracted. Practical consequence: re-syncing a source never rewrites history — old submissions stay bound to their original version; only new submissions pick up the newest version. State withholding versions carry the state code so the right state layout is pinned per submission.\n\n## I-9 Reverification\n\nWhen the employer records Section 2 documents whose work authorization expires, the expiration is stored on the submission as **`I9ReverificationDueAt`**. It stays null for non-expiring evidence (U.S. citizen, lawful permanent resident with a non-expiring document). When set, it drives a reverification reminder so HR is prompted before the authorization lapses — reverification is a fresh employer attestation, distinct from the original Section 2. Don't conflate it with **`I9Section2OverdueAt`** (the 3-business-day deadline to *first* complete Section 2, set when Section 1 is signed); reverification is about expiring authorization later in employment.\n\n## Sensitive-Form Masking\n\nW-4, I-9, and State Withholding are sensitive forms (the `isSensitive` set = `W4`, `I9`, `StateWithholding`). Their truly sensitive fields — SSN, bank routing/account numbers, I-9 document numbers — are stored encrypted server-side and **never echoed back**. The onboarding draft (`GET /onboarding/draft`) returns non-sensitive values plus `Has*` booleans for the sensitive ones rather than the raw value, and validators are relaxed on a sensitive field when the server reports it already has a stored value (so you don't have to re-enter an SSN you already saved). On resubmit of a sensitive form, prior data is **not** pre-filled — the renderer starts clean so a stale ciphertext value isn't surfaced. Submission summaries show only non-sensitive fields (filing status, Yes/No flags) and masked last-4 for direct deposit.\n\n## DocuSeal Recovery\n\nThe signing ceremony can end in a non-completed terminal state. The submission `Status` enum is `Pending` -> `Opened` -> `Completed`, plus the recovery states **`Expired`** (the DocuSeal link lapsed before signing) and **`Declined`** (the signer declined). Recovery is forward-only: there is no \"resume\" of a dead link — the employee starts a **new** submission, which mints a fresh DocuSeal link (and re-pins the current form-definition version). Status flows back via the DocuSeal **webhook** (`POST /webhook`, HMAC-SHA256 signature verified against the configured secret), which is what advances `Opened`/`Completed`/`Declined` and stamps `SignedAt` + the signed PDF. The signing iframe is shown only while `DocuSealSubmitUrl` is present and status is `Pending`/`Opened`; once `Expired`/`Declined`, the iframe is gone and the Start E-Sign path creates the replacement submission.\n\n## System vs Custom Templates\n\nThe six built-in form types (W-4, I-9, State Withholding, Direct Deposit, Workers' Comp, Handbook) ship as **system templates**: they cannot be deleted, and their row edit action is **upload-only** (`upload_file` icon, not `edit`) — you can attach a manual document override and configure PDF fill, but not rename or change the form's core identity. **Custom templates** you create have the full edit dialog (including the AcroField Map textarea) and can be deleted (`delete` icon). Both kinds support extraction, auto-sync, the behavior toggles (Active, Requires Identity Docs, Blocks Job Assignment), and a `ProfileCompletionKey`. The distinction is identity and lifecycle, not capability: system templates are the fixed government/company set every install needs; custom templates are extra forms a particular shop adds.\n","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Compliance Forms training modules");
    }
}
